parts:
Below is the **deterministic (drift‐only) Fokker–Planck/continuity equation** specialized to the Lorenz system. We will:

1. Write down the general continuity equation for a density \(p(x,y,z,t)\) advected by a velocity (drift) field \(\mathbf{f}(x,y,z)\).  
2. Substitute the **Lorenz equations** into that formula.  
3. Identify the resulting PDE terms corresponding to **advection** and **dissipation/volume change**.

---

## 1. General Deterministic Continuity Equation

If \(\dot{\mathbf{x}} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x})\) is your dynamical system and \(p(\mathbf{x},t)\) is a density of “particles” in state space, then in the **absence** of diffusion, \(p\) evolves by:

\[
\frac{\partial p}{\partial t}
\;=\;
-\,\nabla \cdot \bigl[p(\mathbf{x},t)\,\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x})\bigr]
\quad\Longleftrightarrow\quad
\frac{\partial p}{\partial t}
\;=\;
-\,\Bigl[\mathbf{f}\cdot\nabla p \;+\; p\,\bigl(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{f}\bigr)\Bigr].
\]

- The term \(-\,\mathbf{f}\cdot\nabla p\) is the **advection** (convective) transport of \(p\).  
- The term \(-\,p\,(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{f})\) reflects **local volume change** (compression/expansion) in phase space.  

When \(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{f} < 0\) on average (dissipative systems), volumes shrink in state space, and the density tends to “pile up” onto lower-dimensional sets (attractors).

---

## 2. The Lorenz System

The **Lorenz equations** for state \(\mathbf{x}=(x,y,z)\) are

\[
\begin{cases}
\dot{x} \;=\; f_1(x,y,z) \;=\; \sigma \,\bigl(y - x\bigr),\\[6pt]
\dot{y} \;=\; f_2(x,y,z) \;=\; x\,(r - z)\;-\;y,\\[6pt]
\dot{z} \;=\; f_3(x,y,z) \;=\; x\,y \;-\; b\,z.
\end{cases}
\]

Here \(\sigma,\,r,\,b\) are constants (e.g.\ \(\sigma=10,\; r=28,\; b=\tfrac{8}{3}\)).

### 2.1. Compute \(\nabla\cdot \mathbf{f}\)

\[
\nabla \cdot \mathbf{f}
\;=\;
\frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x}
\;+\;
\frac{\partial f_2}{\partial y}
\;+\;
\frac{\partial f_3}{\partial z}.
\]

- \(\partial_x f_1 = \partial_x\bigl[\sigma(y-x)\bigr] = -\,\sigma.\)  
- \(\partial_y f_2 = \partial_y\bigl[x(r-z) - y\bigr] = -\,1.\)  
- \(\partial_z f_3 = \partial_z\bigl[x\,y - b\,z\bigr] = -\,b.\)

Hence,

\[
\nabla \cdot \mathbf{f}
\;=\;
-\,\sigma \;-\; 1 \;-\; b
\;=\;
-\;\bigl(\sigma + 1 + b\bigr).
\]

---

## 3. Putting It All Together

Plugging \(\mathbf{f}=(f_1,f_2,f_3)\) into the continuity equation,

\[
\frac{\partial p}{\partial t}
\;=\;
-\,\nabla \cdot \bigl[p\,\mathbf{f}\bigr]
\;=\;
-\,\bigl[
    f_1\,\partial_x p \;+\;
    f_2\,\partial_y p \;+\;
    f_3\,\partial_z p
\;+\;
    p\,(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{f})
\bigr].
\]

But we just found \(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{f} = -(\sigma + 1 + b)\), so

\[
\frac{\partial p}{\partial t}
\;=\;
-\;\Bigl[
     \sigma(y - x)\,\frac{\partial p}{\partial x}
   \;+\;
     \bigl(x(r - z)\;-\;y\bigr)\,\frac{\partial p}{\partial y}
   \;+\;
     \bigl(x\,y\;-\;b\,z\bigr)\,\frac{\partial p}{\partial z}
   \Bigr]
\;-\;
p\,\Bigl[-(\sigma + 1 + b)\Bigr].
\]

The last term simplifies to \(+\,(\sigma + 1 + b)\,p\). Therefore, the **deterministic Fokker–Planck/continuity equation** for the Lorenz system is:

\[
\boxed{
\frac{\partial p}{\partial t}
\;=\;
-\;\Bigl[
     \sigma(y - x)\,\frac{\partial p}{\partial x}
   \;+\;
     \bigl(x(r - z)\;-\;y\bigr)\,\frac{\partial p}{\partial y}
   \;+\;
     \bigl(x\,y\;-\;b\,z\bigr)\,\frac{\partial p}{\partial z}
   \Bigr]
\;+\;
(\sigma + 1 + b)\,p.
}
\]

---

### Interpretation of the Two Key Terms

1. **Advection (Convective) Part**  
   \[
     -\,\Bigl[
     \sigma(y-x)\,\partial_x p
     + (x(r-z)-y)\,\partial_y p
     + (xy - b\,z)\,\partial_z p
     \Bigr].
   \]
   This represents the “flow” of density along the vector field \(\mathbf{f}\).

2. **Volume-Change (Dissipation) Part**  
   \[
     \quad+\,(\sigma + 1 + b)\,p
     \quad\leftrightarrow\quad
     -\,p\,\bigl[\nabla\cdot\mathbf{f}\bigr],
   \]
   which is nonzero because \(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{f}\neq 0\).  In fact, \(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{f} = -(\sigma+1+b)\), so the flow is **volume‐shrinking** (dissipative) in phase space, causing the density \(p\) to increase along directions of contraction.

That completes the derivation of the **deterministic part** of the Fokker–Planck equation for the Lorenz system.
